There are 155 observations and 8 variables. You can find more information about the variables here: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/TuomoNieminen/Helsinki-Open-Data-Science/master/datasets/human_meta.txt Many of the variables seem to be normally distributed while for example Mat.Mor and GNI are not. There is a strong negative correlation between the variables Life.Exp and Mat.Mor and strong positive correlation between the variables Life.Exp and Edu.Exp

Perform principal component analysis (PCA)

pcahuman <- prcomp(human)
summarypcahuman <- summary(pcahuman)
summarypcahuman

Standardize the variables and repeat the above analysis

humanstd <- scale(human)
pcahumanstd <- prcomp(humanstd)
s_humanstd <- summary(pcahumanstd)
s_humanstd
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4     PC5     PC6     PC7
## Standard deviation     2.0708 1.1397 0.87505 0.77886 0.66196 0.53631 0.45900
## Proportion of Variance 0.5361 0.1624 0.09571 0.07583 0.05477 0.03595 0.02634
## Cumulative Proportion  0.5361 0.6984 0.79413 0.86996 0.92473 0.96069 0.98702
##                            PC8
## Standard deviation     0.32224
## Proportion of Variance 0.01298
## Cumulative Proportion  1.00000
pca_pr <- round(100*s_humanstd$importance[2, ], digits = 1)
pca_lab <- paste0(names(pca_pr), " (", pca_pr, "%)")
biplot(pcahumanstd, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.6, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pca_lab[1], ylab = pca_lab[2])
